thyroid gland"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIodothyronine deiodinases remove iodine atoms from thyroid hormones\u003C/strong\u003E at specific positions, converting T4 to either active T3 or inactive reverse T3. This process occurs predominantly in peripheral tissues.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThe circulating pool lasting 24 hours\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect - T4 has a half-life of approximately 7 days while T3 has a half-life of about 1 day\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMost thyroid hormones circulating unbound\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect - approximately 99.97% of T4 and 99.7% of T3 are bound to transport proteins\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFree T3 comprising 5%\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect - only about 0.3% of total T3 circulates in its free form\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ET4 conversion to T3 mainly within the thyroid\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect - this occurs predominantly in peripheral tissues such as the liver and kidneys\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe high protein binding and long half-life of thyroid hormones helps maintain stable hormone levels in the circulation.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Thyroid hormones are primarily bound to transport proteins with only 0.02% of T4 and 0.3% of T3 being free in circulation","The extrathyroidal pool of thyroid hormones has a long half-life of several days","Iodothyronine deiodinases remove iodine from specific positions to convert T4 to T3 or reverse T3"],"references":["Brent GA. Mechanisms of thyroid hormone action. J Clin Invest. 2012 Sep;122(9):3035-43. doi: 10.1172/JCI60047. Epub 2012 Sep 4. PMID: 22945636; PMCID: PMC3433956.","Melmed, S., Polonsky, K. S., Larsen, P. R., \u0026 Kronenberg, H. M. (2015). Williams textbook of endocrinology E-Book.